{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/repnet-counting-repeating-actions-in-a-video-bec1bdcec149", "time": 1683012881.598785, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/repnet-counting-repeating-actions-in-a-video-bec1bdcec149/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "RepNet: Counting Repeating Actions in a Video | by Param Raval | Towards Data Science", "h1": "RepNet: Counting Repeating Actions in a Video", "description": "While most of us can keep count while exercising or measuring the pulse, it would be great to have something to keep count for us and even provide valuable information about the repeated actions\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "https://deepmind.com/research/open-source/kinetics", "anchor_text": "Kinetics here", "paragraph_index": 5}, {"url": "https://deepmind.com/research/open-source/kinetics", "anchor_text": "Kinetics", "paragraph_index": 6}, {"url": "https://colab.research.google.com/github/google-research/google-research/blob/master/repnet/repnet_colab.ipynb", "anchor_text": "Colab Notebook", "paragraph_index": 9}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/param-raval/", "anchor_text": "LinkedIn", "paragraph_index": 13}, {"url": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/param-raval/", "anchor_text": "https://www.linkedin.com/in/param-raval/", "paragraph_index": 15}], "all_paragraphs": ["While most of us can keep count while exercising or measuring the pulse, it would be great to have something to keep count for us and even provide valuable information about the repeated actions. Especially for actions with a longer period like planetary cycles or periods that are too short like a manufacturing belt.", "A recent paper by the Google Research & DeepMind team, published in CPVR 2020, called Counting Out Time: Class Agnostic Video Repetition Counting in the Wild addresses this interesting problem.", "They employ a pretty \u201csimple\u201d approach to identifying and counting repeated actions, and eventually predicting the periodicity of the action. But the main hurdle the authors identify is curating a large enough dataset to be able to do this. Thus, this paper[1] mainly contributes in:", "The authors, before anything else, propose a new, HUGE dataset of annotated videos with repeating actions \u2014 since the existing datasets for repetition are just too small.", "Look at the figure above that compares the new dataset: Countix with the existing \u201cbenchmark\u201d (which has merely 100 samples!). Countix has videos taken from the wild (like YouTube) and the team gathered annotations by crowd-sourcing them. The annotators \u201csegment the part of the video that contains valid repetitions with unambiguous counts\u201d[1]. And they proceed to add the count value as well. A nifty process that eventually led to an annotated dataset that was 90 times bigger than the previous ones.", "Take a look at Kinetics here", "In addition to Countix (which takes its clips from Kinetics), the authors propose a cool way of generating synthetic videos from normal videos that resemble real repeating videos.", "To be concise, what they do is:", "The model architecture is composed of:", "This very informative Colab Notebook takes you through each step of executing the model and test on a local video as well as on your live webcam", "Can you think of an event or angle that this approach needs to address? Where can this work in the real-world? And where not?", "The paper provides the following real-world applications of RepNet:", "[1]Dwibedi, Debidatta, et al., \u201cCounting Out Time: Class Agnostic Video Repetition Counting in the Wild.\u201d 2020, Proceedings of the IEEE/CVF Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition.", "Thank you for reading all the way through! You can reach out to me on LinkedIn for any messages, thoughts, or suggestions.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "A student of engineering with a zeal for Machine Learning and writing. Reach out to me on LinkedIn: https